24.2.4 Sigma notation: working with sums
A few practical moves.
Evaluating a sum. To evaluate \(\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{4}(3i - 1)\), substitute \(i = 1, 2, 3, 4\) and add:
\[(3 \cdot 1 - 1) + (3 \cdot 2 - 1) + (3 \cdot 3 - 1) + (3 \cdot 4 - 1)\] \[= 2 + 5 + 8 + 11 = 26\]
You can check this with the arithmetic series formula: \(a_1 = 2\), \(d = 3\), \(n = 4\). \(S_4 = \frac{4}{2}(2 + 11) = 2 \times 13 = 26\). Same answer. This means sigma notation and series formulas are two views of the same sum: one expanded, one compressed.
Changing the index. The index variable is a dummy — it doesn’t matter what letter you use. \(\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i\) and \(\displaystyle\sum_{k=1}^{n} a_k\) are the same sum.
Splitting a sum. You can split a sum that has two parts:
\[\sum_{i=1}^{n}(a_i + b_i) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i + \sum_{i=1}^{n} b_i\]
And pull a constant out:
\[\sum_{i=1}^{n} c \cdot a_i = c \sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i\]
This means sums follow familiar algebra rules, which is why they are so useful later in calculus and physics.

