32.3 The normal distribution
The binomial counts discrete things — 0 heads, 1 head, 2 heads. But heights, weights, temperatures, and exam scores can take any value in a continuous range. For these, you need a different model.
The normal distribution \(N(\mu, \sigma^2)\) is a continuous bell curve centred at \(\mu\) and spreading out by \(\sigma\) in each direction (the second parameter is the variance \(\sigma^2\), not the standard deviation — to find the spread in the original units, take the square root: \(\sigma = \sqrt{\sigma^2}\)). You specify it by two numbers only: the mean and the variance. This means the normal distribution is a family of curves, all with the same bell shape but shifted and stretched by \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\).

32.3.1 Why the bell curve appears everywhere
This is one of the most remarkable results in all of probability: when you add up many independent random influences, the total tends toward the normal distribution — regardless of what the individual influences look like. A person’s height is the sum of contributions from hundreds of genes, years of nutrition, sleep patterns, and dozens of other factors. None of those individually looks like a bell curve. Their sum does.
This is the central limit theorem. You won’t prove it at this stage, but you’ll use it, and you’ll see it confirmed every time you look at data from a natural process. This means the bell curve matters because sums and averages of many small effects tend to produce it.


32.3.2 The 68-95-99.7 rule
For any normal distribution \(N(\mu, \sigma^2)\):



Range
Probability




\(\mu - \sigma\) to \(\mu + \sigma\) (within 1 std dev)
68%


\(\mu - 2\sigma\) to \(\mu + 2\sigma\) (within 2 std dev)
95%


\(\mu - 3\sigma\) to \(\mu + 3\sigma\) (within 3 std dev)
99.7%



This is sometimes called the empirical rule. It gives you a quick sense of what is “normal” variation and what is surprising. This means standard deviations give a practical scale for judging how unusual a value is in a normal setting.
If exam scores are \(N(65, 144)\) — so \(\mu = 65\) and \(\sigma = 12\) — then about 95% of students score between \(65 - 24 = 41\) and \(65 + 24 = 89\). A score of 20 would be genuinely extraordinary (more than 3 standard deviations below the mean), occurring less than 0.15% of the time.


32.3.3 Standardising: the z-score
A practical problem: there is a different normal distribution for every combination of \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\). You can’t carry a different table for each one.
The solution is to convert any normal distribution to a single standard one. The standard normal distribution is \(N(0, 1)\) — mean 0, variance 1.
To convert a value \(x\) from any normal distribution to its standard normal equivalent, compute:
\[z = \frac{x - \mu}{\sigma}\]
The value \(z\) is called a z-score. It tells you how many standard deviations above (positive) or below (negative) the mean the value \(x\) sits. This means standardising translates any normal-distribution problem into one common scale measured in standard deviations.
Once you have \(z\), you look up \(P(Z \leq z)\) in a standard normal table or compute it on a calculator. This single table handles all normal distributions.
Example. Scores are \(N(65, 144)\), so \(\mu = 65\), \(\sigma = 12\). For a score of \(x = 83\):
\[z = \frac{83 - 65}{12} = \frac{18}{12} = 1.5\]
A score of 83 sits 1.5 standard deviations above the mean. A table gives \(P(Z \leq 1.5) \approx 0.933\), so about 93.3% of students scored 83 or below — and about 6.7% scored above 83. This means a z-score is a position statement: it tells you where a value sits relative to the rest of the distribution.


